    "summary": "Kylie Thomas is a Senior Researcher at NIOD Institute for War, Holocaust and Genocide Studies in Amsterdam, where she works as part of the NIOD ImageLab, focusing on war and visual culture from World War Two to the present. She is also a Senior Lecturer at the Radical Humanities Laboratory and School of History, University College Cork, Ireland. She completed her PhD at the University of Cape Town in 2007 and her MA at the University of British Columbia in 1999. She is a transdisciplinary scholar whose work focuses on political violence; feminist, LGBT and anti-racist activism and art; and the history and theory of photography, with a particular focus on South Africa during and after apartheid. She held a Marie Curie Research Fellowship at NIOD from 2019-2021. She was a non-resident Research Associate at the Institute for Reconciliation and Social Justice at the University of the Free State, South Africa from 2016-2019. From June - February 2018 she held a British Academy Visiting Research Fellowship at the University of Brighton. From September 2017 - June 2018 she held a European Institutes for Advanced Study Junior Visiting Research Fellowship at the Institute for Human Sciences, Vienna, Austria, where she conducted research for a book on women photographers and resistance to repressive regimes. In 2018 she was awarded a visiting research fellowship at the Peter Wall Institute at the University of British Columbia in Canada and In 2017 she held a European Holocaust Research Infrastructure Fellowship at the Netherlands Institute for War, Holocaust and Genocide Studies in Amsterdam, and was a visiting research fellow at the Moore Institute, National University of Galway; at the Humanities Institute, University College, Dublin, Ireland and at the African Studies Centre, Leiden. \n\nShe is the author of Impossible Mourning: HIV/AIDS and Visuality after apartheid; co-editor of two books on photography in Africa; as well as numerous articles on photography, history and violence.",
